n\u2013Dunlop || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+10h 05' 23\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |26\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jan Mertens (cyclist)|Jan Mertens]]|BEL}} || Labor\u2013Dunlop || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+10h 27' 05\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |27\n| {{flagathlete|[[Paul Duboc]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+10h 30' 47\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |28\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Delannoy]]|BEL}} || Labor\u2013Dunlop || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+10h 41' 09\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |29\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Dhers]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+11h 26' 16\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |30\n| {{flagathlete|[[Carlo Longoni]]|ITA|1861}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+11h 50' 56\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |31\n| {{flagathlete|[[Charles Martinet (cyclist)|Charles Martinet]]|SUI}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+12h 56' 13\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |32\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fernand Saive]]|BEL}} || Meteore\u2013Wolber || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+13h 59' 59\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |33\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Arnoult]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+14h 24' 52\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |34\n| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Catelan]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+15h 53' 32\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |35\n| {{flagathlete|[[Mose Arrosio]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+17h 12' 30\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |36\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fernand Moulet]]|FRA}} || Meteore\u2013Wolber || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+18h 00' 43\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |37\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alfred Francini]]|ITA|1861}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+18h 18' 25\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |38\n| {{flagathlete|[[Edouard Teisseire]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+19h 14' 17\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |39\n| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Ferrara]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+21h 00' 22\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |40\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jules Gillard]]|SUI}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+22h 47' 44\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |41\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Drobecq]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" |+24h 59' 03\"\n|}\n\n==Other classifications==\nThe race for ''touriste-routiers'', cyclists who did not belong to a team and were allowed no assistance, was won by Italian Rossignoli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1926/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour - Ann\u00e9e 1926|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=15 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709024743/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1926/histoire.html|archive-date=9 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe organising newspaper, [[l'Auto]] named a ''meilleur grimpeur'' (best climber), an unofficial precursor to the modern [[King of the Mountains]] competition. This award was won by Lucien Buysse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|title=Tour-giro-vuelta|accessdate=21 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nLucien Buysse announced after his win that he expected to win again in 1927, but because his sponsor Automoto had financial problems, they could not send a team to the Tours of 1927 and 1928, and Buysse only returned in 1929.<ref name=\"trouw\"/> Lucien Buysse would never finish the Tour de France again. The winner of the previous edition, Bottecchia, said that he would retire from cycling, after the difficulties he faced in the 1926 Tour de France.\n\nThe Tour de France organisation did not like the outcome of the 1926 Tour de France, as 10 of the 17 stages had finished in bunch sprints. For the next year, the rules were changed, and the flat stages were run as team time trials.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=80\u201384}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1926|1926 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1926 Tour de France|1|9|10|17}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1926 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1926 in road cycling]]\n[[Category:1926 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year|1926]]\n[[Category:June 1926 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1926 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1926 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1926.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1926 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Evian,<br /> going counter-clockwise around France, and then to Paris.\n| image_alt          = Map of France with 17 cities shown, connected by red lines. Most of the shown cities are close to the border, except the ones labeled \"Dijon\" and \"Paris\".\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 20 June \u2013 18 July\n| stages             = 17\n| distance           = 5745\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 238h 44' 25\"\n| first              = [[Lucien Buysse]]\n| first_nat          = BEL\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Automoto\u2013Hutchinson\n| second             = [[Nicolas Frantz]]\n| second_nat         = LUX\n| second_team        = Alcyon\u2013Dunlop\n| third              = [[Bartolom\u00e9o Aymo]]\n| third_nat          = ITA\n| third_natvar       = 1861\n| third_team         = Alcyon\u2013Dunlop\n| previous           = [[1925 Tour de France|1925]]\n| next               = [[1927 Tour de France|1927]]\n}}\nThe '''1926 Tour de France''' was the 20th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 20 June to 18 July. It consisted of 17 stages with a total distance of 5745&nbsp;km, ridden at an average speed of 24.064&nbsp;km/h.\n\nThe longest tour in history,{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} the route traced closely the borders of [[France]]. It was the first time that the race started outside [[Paris]];{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} in this way riders were forced to climb the mountains in the east of the country twice, once at the beginning of the race, and again at the end.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1926.php|title=1926: The longest Tour|accessdate=21 September 2009|date=15 August 2003|author=Tom James|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref> The race was won by Belgian cyclist [[Lucien Buysse]].\n\n==Changes from previous Tour==\nIn 1925, the number of stages had been increased from 15 (which was common since 1910) to 18 stages. In 1926, this was decreased to 17 stages. Tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] wanted to have longer stages, so the average stage length increased from 312&nbsp;km per stage in 1925 to 338&nbsp;km per stage in 1926.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=80\u201384}}\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1926 Tour de France}}\n\nThere were 126 cyclists who started the Tour de France; 82 of them were touriste-routiers, cyclists who did not have the support from a team. The other 44 cyclists started the race in teams; some teams only had two cyclists.<ref name=\"mdc1926\"/>\n\n==Pre-race favourites==\nThe two teams with favourites were Automoto and Alcyon. The Automoto team had [[Ottavio Bottecchia]], the winner of the last two editions of the race, and [[Lucien Buysse]], the runner-up of the previous edition. The Alcyon team had [[Bartolomeo Aymo]] and [[Nicolas Frantz]], third and fourth in 1925. They also had [[Adelin Benoit]], and the Tour organisation thought that the battle would be between Bottecchia and Benoit.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=80\u201384}}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9|1926 Tour de France, Stage 10 to Stage 17}}\n[[File:Buysse gadegeslagen door een koe Buysse passing a cow.jpg|thumb|[[Jules Buysse]] leading, who will win the first stage (Evian to Mulhouse).]]\n[[Jules Buysse]] started strong in the first stage, by finishing solo with a margin of more than 13 minutes. The second stage ended with a bunch sprint, so nothing changed in the general classification. In the third stage, he lost the lead to Gustaaf van Slembrouck. On that day, Lucien Buysse received the news that his daughter had died. He considered to leave the race, but decided to stay.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=80\u201384}}\nThe next stages all ended in bunch sprints, with all the favourites in the first group. In the sixth stage, [[F\u00e9lix Sellier]] won the sprint. However, the jury decided that he had not sprinted according to the rules, and he was set back to second place, making [[Joseph van Dam]] the winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1926_6.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131005/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1926_6.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=19\u00e8me Tour de France 1926 - 6\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French}}</ref>\n\nThe battle for the general classification seriously began in the tenth stage. That tenth stage was a tough stage, and has been labeled as the toughest stage ever in the Tour de France;<ref name=\"trouw\">{{cite news|url=http://www.trouw.nl/achtergrond/deverdieping/article1309466.ece?all=true|title=Tour de France / De zwaarste etappe ooit|work=Trouw|author=Sierksma, Pieter|date=27 June 2006|accessdate=27 September 2010|language=Dutch}}</ref> 76 cyclists started the race at midnight, and more than seventeen hours later, Lucien Buysse arrived as the winner. After twenty-five minutes, the next cyclist came in. After one hour, only 10 cyclists had finished, so the Tour de France organisation sent cars to look for the cyclists.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> At midnight, 47 cyclists had arrived, some of them in buses.<ref name=\"letour.fr\" /> The race officials decided to allow the cyclists 40% more time than the winning cyclist.<ref name=\"mdc1926-10\"/> Later that night, 54 cyclists had crossed the finish line, and the remaining 22 cyclists were gathered; they were no longer in the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> After the stage, the race officials were approached by a man who claimed that he had brought some cyclists to the finish line with his car, but that the cyclists had not paid him. The officials decided not to punish the cyclists, and paid the driver.<ref name=\"mdc1926-10\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1926_10.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131012/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1926_10.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=19\u00e8me Tour de France 1926 - 10\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French}}</ref> [[Gustaaf Van Slembrouck]], wearing the yellow jersey as leader of the general classification, officially finished in 20th place, two hours behind Buysse. Year later, Van Slembrouck said that during the stage he had said to Tour organiser Desgrange that he was giving up, and Desgrange ordered a car to bring Van Slembrouck to the finish.<ref name=\"trouw\"/> The same stage with the same mountains had also been in the [[1913 Tour de France]]; then the weather was better, and winner [[Philippe Thys]] only took 13 hours to finish the stage.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> One of the cyclists who had not finished the stage was the defending champion, [[Ottavio Bottecchia]].<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1926/histoire.html|title=Historique du Tour - 1926|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=21 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716154702/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1926/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhen Buysse also won the next stage, his victory was assured,<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/> as he was leading by more than one hour.<ref name=\"mdc1926\"/> From that moment, Buysse saved his energy, and the race continued for the second place between Frantz and Aimo.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=80\u201384}} At the end of the race, Frantz was in second place, only 26 seconds before Aimo.\n\n==Results==\nIn each stage, all cyclists started together. The cyclist who reached the finish first, was the winner of the stage.\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish the stage was recorded. For the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], these times were added up; the cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.\n\n===Stage winners===\nIn 1926, there were no French stage winners. This was the first time that this happened, and has since only happened again in [[1999 Tour de France|1999]].<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1926\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1926.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306130900/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1926.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=20\u00e8me Tour de France 1926|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6295874.image.f3.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|work=Le Petit Journal|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique|date=19 June 1926|language=French|page=4|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=24}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1926|title=Tour de France GC top ten|author=Arian Zwegers|publisher=CVCC|accessdate=21 September 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|There was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 June|| [[\u00c9vian-les-Bains|Evian]] to [[M\u00fclhausen]] ||{{convert|373|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jules Buysse]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Jules Buysse]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 June|| [[M\u00fclhausen]] to [[Metz]] ||{{convert|334|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Aim\u00e9 Dossche]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Jules Buysse]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 June|| [[Metz]] to [[Dunkerque]] ||{{convert|433|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Gustaaf van Slembrouck]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Gustaaf van Slembrouck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 26 June|| [[Dunkerque]] to [[Le Havre]] ||{{convert|361|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[F\u00e9lix Sellier]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Gustaaf van Slembrouck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 28 June|| [[Le Havre]] to [[Cherbourg]] ||{{convert|357|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Adelin Benoit]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Gustaaf van Slembrouck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 30 June|| [[Cherbourg]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]] ||{{convert|405|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Joseph van Dam]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Gustaaf van Slembrouck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 July|| [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Les Sables d'Olonne]] ||{{convert|412|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Nicolas Frantz]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Gustaaf van Slembrouck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 July|| [[Les Sables d'Olonne]] to [[Bordeaux]] ||{{convert|285|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Joseph van Dam]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Gustaaf van Slembrouck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1926 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 9#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 July|| [[Bordeaux]] to [[Bayonne]] ||{{convert|189|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Nicolas Frantz]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Gustaaf van Slembrouck]]|BEL}}\n|-\